HTTP/2 

HTTP/2 is a faster version of HTTP/1.1.

Problem with HTTP/1.1
- It handles one request at a time. If a webpage needs HTML, CSS, and JS, it loads them one by one.
- It opens and closes the connection again and again. This wastes time.
- It sends data as plain text. Plain text is heavy and slow.

How HTTP/2 Fixes These Problems

1. Multiplexing

HTTP/1.1 sends requests one by one like standing in a line.
HTTP/2 sends all requests at the same time over one connection.

Real benefit for IT working:
If one request is slow, it does not block others. APIs and microservices work faster because they can handle many calls together without waiting.

2. Binary Protocol

HTTP/1.1 uses plain text which takes more space.
HTTP/2 uses binary format which is smaller and faster to read.

Real benefit for IT working:
Less data transfer means lower bandwidth cost and faster response time for users and servers.

3. Server Push

Normally the browser asks for HTML, then CSS, then JS.
In HTTP/2, the server can send CSS and JS before the browser even asks.

Real benefit for IT working:
Pages load faster without extra round trips. Good for Progressive Web Apps where speed matters.

4. Single Connection

HTTP/1.1 opens many connections. Each connection takes time.
HTTP/2 uses one single connection for everything.

Real benefit for IT working:
Less CPU and memory usage on the server. Better for systems with many small requests like chat apps or live updates.

Where HTTP/2 is Used
Modern websites like Google, YouTube, Facebook.
APIs and microservices where many small calls happen.
Progressive Web Apps that need fast loading.

Quick Comparison
Feature	        HTTP/1.1    	HTTP/2
Multiplexing	No	            Yes
Data format	    Text	        Binary
Server push	    No	            Yes
Connections	    Multiple	    Single
Best for	    Simple websites	Modern web, APIs, microservices

Final Simple Verdict
HTTP/1.1 is like an old bicycle.
HTTP/2 is like a modern car. Faster, smoother, and built for today's internet.

